</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Raised Bed Planning Needs Different Prompts</h2>
  <p>A raised bed is not just a smaller version of an in-ground garden. It has hard edges, limited square footage, faster drainage, easier access, and often warmer soil in spring. Those are advantages, but they also force tradeoffs.</p>
  <p>In a 4x8 bed, one indeterminate tomato with a sturdy trellis can be reasonable. Four sprawling tomato plants, three zucchini, cucumbers, carrots, lettuce, basil, beans, and melons in the same bed is a problem. AI may not recognize that unless you explicitly tell it to avoid overcrowding.</p>
  <p>Raised bed planning is really a series of decisions: which crops deserve space, which crops should be trellised, which crops can be succession planted, which crops belong on the edges, and which crops should be saved for another year. AI is useful because it can help make those decisions visible.</p>
  <p>The goal is not to make AI draw the perfect map. The goal is to use AI to create a realistic plan you can understand, edit, and check against your actual growing season.</p>

</section>

